Lab 4: Statistics

Historgrams, Barplots, Lineplots

Author

Bogdan G. Popescu

1 Intro

In this lab, we will continue with the basics of ggplot and will focus on barplots and lineplots. We will also conver once again the basics of histograms. As described in class histograms allow us to better understand how frequently or infrequently certain values occur in our dataset.

To unserstand better how histograms work, imagine a set of values that are spaced out along a number line.

To construct a histogram, a section of the number line is divided into equal chunks, called bins. Next, count how many data points sit inside each bin, and draw bars, one for each bin, whose heights correspond to the number of data points.

Label the data (in the example below each data point is an SAT score), draw in a y-axis which counts the number of data points in each bin, and finally label your bins.

3 Create averages

The next step is to create averages for all the countries

library(dplyr)
life_expectancy_df2 <- life_expectancy_df %>%
    dplyr::group_by(Code) %>%
    dplyr::summarize(life_exp_mean = mean(Life.expectancy.at.birth..historical.))

urbanization_df2 <- urbanization_df %>%
    dplyr::group_by(Code) %>%
    dplyr::summarize(urb_mean = mean(Urban.population....of.total.population.))

4.1 Cleaning our dataset

weird_labels <- c("OWID_KOS", "OWID_WRL", "")

4.2 Performing a left merge

We will now perform a left merge whereby we try to merge urbanization data to life expectancy based on Code.

merged_data<-left_join(clean_life_expectancy_df, clean_urbanization_df, by = c("Code"="Code"))

5.1 Calculating the mean

We already know how to calculate the mean for our dataset. This is 61.243 which is obtained by typing mean(merged_data2$life_exp_mean_rounded)

Let us put it in our graph.

mean_life_expectancy<-mean(merged_data2$life_exp_mean_rounded)
fig6<-ggplot(data = freq_table, aes(x=life_exp_mean_rounded, y=frequency))+
  geom_bar(stat="identity")+
  theme_bw()+
  geom_vline(xintercept=mean_life_expectancy, linetype='dashed', col = 'red')

fig6

5.2 Adding the mean to the graph

Let us add some some text to indicate that the line is the mean life expectancy in our dataset. The way to do this is by using annotate.

Here is how we can do that.

text_to_add<-"Mean"
y_coord<-11
x_coord<-mean((merged_data2$life_exp_mean_rounded))

mean_life_expectancy<-mean((merged_data2$life_exp_mean_rounded))
fig6<-ggplot(data = freq_table, aes(x=life_exp_mean_rounded, y=frequency))+
  geom_bar(stat="identity")+
  theme_bw()+
  geom_vline(xintercept=mean_life_expectancy, linetype='dashed', col = 'red')+
  annotate(geom="text", 
           x=x_coord, 
           y=y_coord, 
           label=text_to_add,
              color="red")

fig6

Maybe we want to move the text a bit further to the left. We can subtract 2 from the x_coord.

text_to_add<-"Mean"
y_coord<-11
x_coord<-mean((merged_data2$life_exp_mean_rounded))-2

mean_life_expectancy<-mean((merged_data2$life_exp_mean_rounded))
fig6<-ggplot(data = freq_table, aes(x=life_exp_mean_rounded, y=frequency))+
  geom_bar(stat="identity")+
  theme_bw()+
  geom_vline(xintercept=mean_life_expectancy, linetype='dashed', col = 'red')+
  annotate(geom="text", 
           x=x_coord, 
           y=y_coord, 
           label=text_to_add,
              color="red")

fig6

6 Creating a line plot

An important question is understanding how life expectancy might have evolved over time. Let us go back to the original dataset before calculating the averages.

head(life_expectancy_df, n=6)
#Renaming variable
names(life_expectancy_df)[4]<-"life_exp_yearly"
head(life_expectancy_df, n=6)
fig7<-ggplot(data = life_expectancy_df, aes(x = Year, y = life_exp_yearly))+
  geom_line(aes(color = Entity))+
  theme_bw()+
  guides(color = "none")
fig7

Unfortunately, we cannot make out much out of this graph, as we have way too many countries. It probably makes sense to focus on 1-2 coutries. Letâs take the US and the UK as an example.

6.1 Subsetting the sample to fewer countries

countries_of_interest<-c("United States", "United Kingdom")
df_us_uk<-subset(life_expectancy_df, Entity %in% countries_of_interest)
head(df_us_uk, n=10)

Let us now plot life expectancy only for the US and the UK.

fig8<-ggplot(data = df_us_uk, aes(x = Year, y = life_exp_yearly))+
  geom_line(aes(color = Entity))+
  theme_bw()

fig8

6.2 Subsetting the sample to fewer years

It is kind of cool that in the UK, there is data that goes so far back. For comparison purposes, it might be a good idea to restrict our sample to the period after 1900.

df_us_uk_after1900<-subset(df_us_uk, Year>1900)
head(df_us_uk_after1900, n=10)
fig9<-ggplot(data = df_us_uk_after1900, aes(x = Year, y = life_exp_yearly))+
  geom_line(aes(color = Entity))+
  theme_bw()

fig9

Letâs color the two countries in red and blue so that the difference is clearer.

fig9<-ggplot(data = df_us_uk_after1900, aes(x = Year, y = life_exp_yearly))+
  geom_line(aes(color = Entity))+
  theme_bw()+
  scale_color_manual(values=c('Red','Blue'))

fig9

What is the year with the lowest life expectancy for the US?

#Creating a new df with the US
df_us_after1900<-subset(df_us_uk_after1900, Entity=="United States")
df_us_after1900$Year[df_us_after1900$life_exp_yearly==min(df_us_after1900$life_exp_yearly)]
[1] 1918

What is the year with the second lowest life expectancy for the US?

#Arranging and creating a new dataframe
df <- df_us_after1900 %>% arrange(life_exp_yearly)
#Selecting the second lowest
second_highest_life_expectancy <- df$life_exp_yearly[2]
#Selecting the year with the second lowest
df$Year[df$life_exp_yearly==second_highest_life_expectancy]
[1] 1901

What is the year with the lowest life expectancy for the UK?

#Creating a new df with the UK
df_uk_after1900<-subset(df_us_uk_after1900, Entity=="United Kingdom")
df_uk_after1900$Year[df_uk_after1900$life_exp_yearly==min(df_uk_after1900$life_exp_yearly)]
[1] 1901
